'''Gaussian Quantum Monte Carlo''' is a [[quantum Monte Carlo]] method that shows a potential solution to the [[Numerical sign problem|fermion sign problem]] without the deficiencies of alternative approaches. Instead of the [[Hilbert space]], this method works in the space of [[Density matrix|density matrices]] that can be spanned by an over-complete basis of gaussian operators using only positive coefficients. Containing only quadratic forms of the fermionic operators, no anti-commuting variables occur and any quantum state can be expressed as a real probability distribution.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Corney|first=J. F.|last2=Drummond|first2=P. D.|date=2004-12-20|title=Gaussian Quantum Monte Carlo Methods for Fermions and Bosons|url=https://link.aps.org/doi/10.1103/PhysRevLett.93.260401|journal=Physical Review Letters|volume=93|issue=26|pages=260401|doi=10.1103/PhysRevLett.93.260401}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Assaad|first=F. F.|last2=Werner|first2=P.|last3=Corboz|first3=P.|last4=Gull|first4=E.|last5=Troyer|first5=M.|date=2005-12-30|title=Symmetry projection schemes for Gaussian Monte Carlo methods|url=https://link.aps.org/doi/10.1103/PhysRevB.72.224518|journal=Physical Review B|volume=72|issue=22|pages=224518|doi=10.1103/PhysRevB.72.224518}}</ref>

