'''Milton Abramowitz''' (1915 in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]] – 5 July 1958) was a [[mathematics|mathematician]] at the [[NIST|National Bureau of Standards]] who, with [[Irene Stegun]], edited a classic book of mathematical tables called ''[[Abramowitz and Stegun|Handbook of Mathematical Functions]]'', widely known as ''[[Abramowitz and Stegun]]''. Abramowitz died of a heart attack in 1958, at which time the book was not yet completed but was well underway. Stegun took over management of the project and was able to finish the work by 1964, working under the direction of the NBS Chief of [[Numerical Analysis]] [[Philip J. Davis]], who was also a contributor to the book.

The major work of producing reliable mathematical tables, as described above, was part of the [[Works Progress Administration|WPA]] project of [[Franklin Roosevelt]].

